  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Valuing a highly leveraged, slow-growth business means tiny changes in discount rates or growth assumptions swing the equity value drastically.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>Notice the extreme sensitivity. If required return jumps to 8.5%, intrinsic value plunges. If the market accepts a 6.5% yield on AT&amp;T's stability, it becomes highly undervalued. This is the math of a debt-heavy utility.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Faster Deleveraging:</strong> If AT&amp;T pays down debt aggressively, interest expenses fall, boosting FCF faster than modeled.</li>
    <li><strong>Fiber Expansion Success:</strong> Accelerated uptake of high-margin fiber broadband could re-accelerate revenue growth above 3%.</li>
    <li><strong>Industry Consolidation/Pricing:</strong> A more rational competitive environment between T, VZ, and TMUS could improve pricing power and ARPU (Average Revenue Per User).</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Lead Cable Liabilities:</strong> Potential massive legal and cleanup costs related to legacy lead-sheathed copper cables are not fully modeled in base FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>Interest Rate Environment:</strong> A "higher for longer" interest rate environment would make refinancing AT&amp;T's massive debt pile much more expensive, crushing FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>Intense Competition:</strong> T-Mobile or cable companies aggressively stealing mobility market share could force AT&amp;T to lower prices and erode margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital Intensity:</strong> 6G or new network requirements could force an unexpected spike in capex, directly reducing FCF.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of dividend yield models for AT&amp;T?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While AT&amp;T is heavily owned for its dividend, dividends are discretionary. DCF measures the <em>capacity</em> to pay dividends, service debt, and grow. A company can maintain a high dividend yield while eroding intrinsic value by underinvesting. DCF captures the whole picture.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the discount rate (7.5%) lower than tech stocks?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Telecoms operate as near-utilities. Their cash flows are predictable and insulated from severe economic shocks (people pay their phone bills even in recessions). This lowers the business risk and beta, reducing the required rate of return compared to volatile tech stocks.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the massive debt affect this valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">It has a huge impact. Our Enterprise Value calculates the value of the whole business (~$335B). But debt holders have first claim on $155B of that. The equity (stock) is just the remainder. This leverage magnifies both upside and downside for equity holders.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework. AT&amp;T looks fairly valued to slightly undervalued based on these assumptions. Investors must decide if they are comfortable with the high debt load and intense competitive risks.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

